    <segment id="1" parent="20" relname="span">
According to the International Organization for Standardization, usability is 
the &quot;effectiveness, efficiency, and satisfaction with which specified users achieve 
specified goals in particular environments&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="1" relname="justify"> (The HCI Space, 1999).</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="13" relname="span">  With this definition 
we see that the attributes of usability are influenced by the users themselves, the goal or 
the task that must be accomplished, and the environment or system that is being used.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="2" relname="elaboration">  
In dealing with the users, many usability attributes are affected by the user&apos;s own 
enthusiasm, skills and efforts.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="13" relname="volitional-result">  This why there is varying opinions about the usability of a 
single application.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="17" relname="span"> Secondly, usability issues can also be subjected to the task at hand.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="14" relname="volitional-result">  
Tasks that are routine become trivial</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="15" relname="contrast"> and thus usability is greatly increased.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="15" relname="contrast">  On the 
other hand, less routine task hinders usability.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="18" relname="span">  Last, the system or environment that is 
being used can severely affect usability.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="8" relname="elaboration">  Running times, CPU clock speed, the amount of 
RAM, the layout of the application or the options available may have an effect on 
usability.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="22" relname="span">  

It seems as if many of the attributes of usability are affected by all the aforementioned 
issues.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="10" relname="elaboration">  For example learnability depends on the user&apos;s own efforts to learn the process, 
the frequency in which the user performs that process, and the environment in which the 
process takes place.</segment>
